{
  "id": "phekb-ckd-comprehensive",
  "source": "phekb",
  "source_id": "ckd",
  "name": "Chronic Kidney Disease - Comprehensive Provider Query",
  "description": "Simulates a primary care or nephrology provider identifying their complete chronic kidney disease patient population. The Columbia CKD V4.2 algorithm formalizes case definition as: dx + qualifying eGFR + albuminuria, with full stage classification by eGFR (G-stage) and UACR (A-stage). Real-world identification primarily unions: CKD diagnosis codes, reduced eGFR (<60), and elevated UACR (>30 mg/g). The Path C heavy distribution (~35% labs without dx) makes this query especially important \u2014 a Condition-only query will miss most undiagnosed-but-detected CKD.",
  "prompt": "I need to identify my complete chronic kidney disease patient population for a quality improvement initiative on CKD care coordination. From clinical experience, I know CKD is substantially undercoded: only about half of patients with biochemical evidence of CKD (reduced eGFR or proteinuria) have a formal CKD diagnosis on their problem list. Documentation patterns:\n1. Some have a formal CKD diagnosis code with stage (Stage 2, 3, 3A, 3B, or 4)\n2. Many have reduced eGFR below 60 mL/min/1.73 m\u00b2 but no CKD diagnosis ever coded\n3. Some have elevated urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio (above 30 mg/g) indicating proteinuria, regardless of eGFR\n\nPlease run multiple FHIR queries to capture the full population:\n1. Patients with any CKD diagnosis (parent CKD or any of stages 2-4)\n2. Patients with reduced eGFR labs (below 60)\n3. Patients with elevated urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio (above 30 mg/g)\n\nFor each query, return the matching resources. I want the union of all patients found across these three approaches.",
  "metadata": {
    "implementation_guide": "US Core 5.0.0",
    "multi_query": true,
    "algorithm_path": "comprehensive",
    "algorithm_path_description": "Union of CKD dx codes (Paths A+B), reduced eGFR (Paths A+C), and elevated UACR (Paths A+D). Path C is heavy because real-world CKD is substantially undercoded \u2014 many patients with reduced eGFR never receive a formal diagnosis. The PheKB algorithm's full classification operationalized as union for screening, with stage refinement requiring downstream classifier logic.",
    "expected_queries": [
      "Condition?code=http://snomed.info/sct|709044004,http://snomed.info/sct|431856006,http://snomed.info/sct|433144002,http://snomed.info/sct|700378005,http://snomed.info/sct|431857002",
      "Observation?code=http://loinc.org|62238-1&value-quantity=lt60",
      "Observation?code=http://loinc.org|9318-7&value-quantity=gt30"
    ],
